-- Abu Dhabi Islamic, Etisalat, Ma'aden, Sabic, Savola: Gulf Equity Preview
-- Vivian Salama
-- 2010-07-19T05:01:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/abu-dhabi-islamic-etisalat-ma-aden-sabic-savola-gulf-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may rise or
fall in Gulf Arab markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and
prices are from the last close.  
 Dubai’s  DFM General Index  lost 0.8 percent and Qatar’s  QE
Index  dropped 0.7 percent. Saudi Arabia’s  benchmark  retreated
0.3 percent.  
 Abu Dhabi Islamic Bank PJSC  (ADIB UH) The United Arab
Emirates’ second-biggest bank complying with Islamic finance
rules reported a 56 percent increase in second-quarter profit to
301.6 million dirhams ($82 million) as it set aside less money
to cover bad loans. The shares fell 0.4 percent to 2.43 dirhams.  
 Drake & Scull International PJSC  (DSI UH): The Dubai-based
mechanical, electrical and plumbing company was initiated with a
“buy” recommendation and 1.01 dirham price estimate at Global
Investment House. The shares slipped 0.7 percent to 82 fils.  
 Gulf Cement Co.  (GCEM UH): The U.A.E.-based cement producer
reported a second-quarter loss of 19.6 million dirhams after a
profit of 82 million dirhams a year earlier as prices declined.
The shares tumbled 9.9 percent to 1.63 dirhams.  
      Emirates Telecommunications Corp.  (ETISALAT UH): The
U.A.E.’s biggest phone company said second-quarter profit
dropped 21 percent to 1.9 billion dirhams amid competition with
Emirates Integrated Telecommunications Co. for the local phone
market.  
 Separately, Etisalat may buy 26 percent of India’s Reliance
Communications Ltd., a stake estimated to be valued at $3
billion, as early as mid-August, the Financial Times reported,
citing people familiar with the talks. The shares gained 0.5
percent to 10.4 dirhams.  
 Savola Azizia United Co.  (SAVOLA AB): Saudi food producer
said second-quarter profit declined 2.3 percent to 207.7 million
riyals ($55.4 million) as capital gains in the year-ago period
weren’t repeated. The company said it expects a third-quarter
profit of 280 million riyals. The shares rose 0.3 percent to
35.4 riyals.  
 Saudi Basic Industries Corp.  (SABIC AB): The world’s
biggest petrochemicals maker said second-quarter profit almost
tripled to 5 billion riyals on higher prices and as demand for
fertilizers and plastics recovered. The average estimate of
eight analysts was for a profit of 5.7 billion riyals, according
to Bloomberg data. The shares were unchanged at 87.75 riyals.  
 National Shipping Co.  (NSCSA AB): The Saudi operator of
crude oil and chemical tankers said second-quarter profit
increased 23 percent to 132.2 million riyals from a year
earlier. The shares were unchanged at 17.95 riyals.  
 Saudi Arabian Mining Co.  (MAADEN AB) The state-controlled
metals producer known as Ma’aden reported a second-quarter
profit of 31.2 million riyals after a loss of 6.56 million
riyals a year earlier. The shares rose 0.3 percent to 17.8
riyals.  
